k (translated into English for the first time here) opens a new window onto the history of sexuality and the history of sexology and reconfigures our understanding of Richard von Krafft-Ebing's book of the same name, published some forty years later.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aSex (Psychology). 4aConsumer Health & Fitness. 4aGender Studies.1 aHaynes, Melissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKahan, Benjamin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2016z9783110485295oZDB-23-DPM40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170610340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501706103423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501706103/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2016  aZDB-23-DPMb2016